Smoking and the Lung 

Thursday, May 25, 2017 

7:09 PM 

Describe the pathological changes associated with long-term tobacco use 

 

 

 

Briefly describe the natural history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease 

Inhalation of cigarette smoke (or other noxious particles) causes lung inflammation. Chronic inflammation induces parenchymal tissue destruction resulting in emphysema, and disrupts normal repair and defense mechanisms (resulting in small airway fibrosis and structural changes). These changes lead to gas trapping and progressive airflow limitation 

 

Describe the mechanisms that lead to inflammation and damage in COPD and the reason for varying susceptibility between individuals 

Significant exposure to noxious particles or gases leads to airway and alveolar abnormalities through damage to the inner lumen. This leads to chronic inflammation which narrows the small airways and destroys the lung parenchyma (emphysema/destruction of alveoli and enlargement of air spaces). There is a loss of alveolar attachments to the small airways and decreased lung elastic recoil; these changes diminish the ability of the airways to remain open during expiration.  

 

Varying susceptibility 

Factors that influence disease progression are varied. A complex interaction between genes and the environment is very important. Cigarette smoking is not the only risk factor. Risk factors include genes (eg alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency increases susceptibility), environmental exposure, old age, smoking during pregnancy (for child), and females experience more severe COPD than males for the same amount of cigarette smoke. Other factors include lung growth (with regard to children), allergies eg asthma, and respiratory infections.  

 

 

Describe the range of tobacco related cancers in the respiratory tract and their common presentations 

-Adenocarcinoma: 

This is the most common cancer cell type in non-smokers (most patients are smokers nonetheless). This is most common in women, and accounts for half of all lung cancer cases. Histologic diagnosis requires evidence of neoplastic gland formation, pneumocyte marker expression, or intracytoplasmic mucin. There is significant variation in architecture. Neoplastic cells line the alveolar lining, forming infiltrative glands surrounded by inflammation. Characteristics of neoplastic cells include nuclear pleomorphism (increased variation in nuclear size, shape and staining), increased nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio, and hyperchromasia (dark staining of nuclei).  

-Squamous cell carcinoma: 

Diagnosis is predicated on keratin production by tumor cells (normal squamous cells produce keratin), intercellular desmosomes and an immunohistochemistry consistent with known marker expressions of squamous cell carcinoma.  

-Neuroendocrine tumors: small cell carcinoma, large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma, carcinoid tumors  

 

Small cell carcinoma 

Small cell carcinoma is extremely rare in people who haven't smoked. They metastasize early and grow to a large size very quickly, and are therefore the most common primary lung malignancy to cause paraneoplastic syndromes (symptoms caused humoral factors, excreted by cancer cells not in the local area)  and superior vena cava obstruction. This malignancy has the worst prognosis. The tumor cells are very small, no longer than the size of three resting lymphocyte nuclei. They may be round, oval, angulated, and usually have a high nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio. Nuclei are hyperchromatic and have a dispersed, granular chromatin. The tumors are extensively necrotic. Presentation includes a cough, weight loss, dyspnea and chest pain if the tumor is large enough, hemoptysis (coughing up blood), and bone pain.  

 

Large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma 

This is a rare pulmonary tumor, that has a poor prognosis that is only slightly better than small cell carcinoma. Clinical presentation is similar to small cell carcinoma, except large cell neuroendocrine carcinomas tend to be located peripherally rather than centrally, and early stage diagnosis is more common than in small cell carcinoma. They are diagnosed based on high-grade tumor features, the presence of neuroendocrine morphology, and immunohistochemical evidence of neuroendocrine markers.   

 

Carcinoid tumors 

These are rare tumors that appear both centrally and in the periphery. Tumor cells are well defined and have no necrosis. They have round/oval finely granular nuclei, may have acinar structures (look like a berry), and have minimal/no mitotic activity. These metastasize slowly, and have a good prognosis. Symptoms may be absent, but can range widely dependent on location in the body. In the lungs, they cause chest pain, wheezing, dyspnea, weight gain, skin flushing, and pink/purple marks on the skin.  

 

Peripheral airflow limitation 

The extent of inflammation, fibrosis and luminal exudates in the small airways correlates with the reduction in the FEV1 and FEV1/FVC ratio.  

The peripheral airway limitation progressively traps gas during expiration, resulting in static hyperinflation. Static hyperinflation (during rest), reduces inspiratory capacity. During exercise, dynamic hyperinflation occurs as one's respiratory rate increases to further the hyperinflation and increase dyspnea.  

 

Pulmonary hypertension 

Airway obstruction leads to alveolar hypoxia, which leads to pulmonary vasoconstriction of the small pulmonary arteries. This leads to small structural changes. Progressive pulmonary hypertension may lead to right ventricular hypertrophy and right-sided heart failure.  

 

Systemic features 

Inflammatory mediators due to COPD that are in circulation may contribute to skeletal muscle wasting, and may initiate or worsen comorbidities such as ischemic heart disease, heart failure, and diabetes.
